2. Prompt 1 — Pattern Opportunity Identification
Problem Identified
The connect() method uses a long if/elif chain checking self.db_type. Each branch builds a completely different connection string with different parameters, and adding a new database type means editing this method directly — violating the Open/Closed Principle.

Pattern Recommended: Factory Pattern
Aspect	Assessment
Why this fits	Object creation logic varies significantly by type
Benefit	New database types added without touching existing code
Benefit	Each connection type's logic isolated and independently testable
Benefit	Constructor had 11 params - most irrelevant per type (Redis didn't need charset)
Drawback	Adds more classes/files - slight complexity increase for small projects
Drawback	Requires careful design of what's common vs type-specific

Priority: HIGH impact, MEDIUM effort. The 11-parameter constructor is a code smell on its own, and the if/elif chain only gets worse as more database types are added.

